revision.text:
[[File:Ayrton-shunt.jpg|thumb|Ayrton shunt switching principle]]
'''Ayrton shunt''' or '''universal shunt''' is a high-resistance [[Shunt (electrical)|shunt]] used in [[galvanometer]]s to increase their range{{sfn|Basic Electrical Engg: Prin & Appl|2009|p=826}} without changing the [[damping]].{{sfn|Graf|1999|p=50}}
The circuit is named after its inventor [[William E. Ayrton]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/ayrton%20shunt|title=Ayrton shunt|publisher=Merriam-Webster, Incorporated|accessdate=11 January 2014}}</ref> Multirange [[ammeters]] that use this technique are more accurate than those using a make-before-break switch.{{sfn|Herman|2013|p=201}} Also it will eliminate the possibility of having a meter without a shunt which is a serious concern in make-before-break switches.{{sfn|Bakshi|Bakshi|2009|p=3-41}}

The selector switch changes the amount of resistance in parallel with R<sub>m</sub> (meter resistance). The voltage drop across parallel branches is always equal. When all resistances are placed in parallel with R<sub>m</sub> maximum sensitivity of ammeter is reached.{{sfn|Bakshi|Bakshi|2009|p=3-41}}

Ayrton shunt is rarely used for currents above 10 [[amperes]].{{sfn|Herman|2010|p=276}}

