{{Nihongo|'''Seikosha'''|精工舎|Seikōsha}} was a branch of the Japanese company [[Seiko]] that produced clocks, watches, [[Shutter (photography)|shutter]]s, [[computer printer]]s and other devices. It was the root of the manufacturing companies of the [[Seiko Group]].
*1881 &mdash; Kintarō Hattori opens the watch and jewelry shop "[[K. Hattori]]" (''Hattori Tokeiten'' in Japanese; currently named [[Seiko|Seiko Holdings Corporation]]) in the [[Ginza]] area of [[Tokyo]], [[Japan]].<ref name="sii history">{{cite web | title = Seiko Instruments history | publisher = Seiko Instruments | url = http://www.sii.co.jp/corp/eg/company/company3.html | accessdate = 2009-10-02 }}{{en icon}}</ref> *1892 &mdash; Seikosha is established in Tokyo as the clock manufacturing arm of K. Hattori. *1917 &mdash; K. Hattori becomes a company (K. Hattori & Co., Ltd.). *1937 &mdash; The watch production division of Seikosha is split off as {{Nihongo|Daini Seikosha Co., Ltd.|第二精工舎|literally ''The Second Seikosha''}}. *1942 &mdash; Daiwa Kogyo, Ltd. is founded in [[Suwa, Nagano]] by Hisao Yamazaki. *1943 &mdash; Daini Seikosha establishes a factory in Suwa for manufacturing watches with Daiwa Kogyo. *1959 &mdash; Daiwa Kogyo and the Suwa Plant of Daini Seikosha merge to form {{Nihongo|Suwa Seikosha Co., Ltd.|諏訪精工舎}} *1961 &mdash; Shinshu Seiki Co., Ltd. is established as a subsidiary of Suwa Seikosha. *1970 &mdash; Seikosha is split off from K. Hattori & Co., Ltd., and Seikosha Co., Ltd. is incorporated. *1982 &mdash; K. Hattori & Co., Ltd. is renamed Hattori Seiko Co., Ltd. *1982 &mdash; Shinshu Seiki is renamed Epson Corporation. *1983 &mdash; Daini Seikosha is renamed Seiko Instruments & Electronics Ltd. *1985 &mdash; Suwa Seikosha and Epson merge to form [[Seiko Epson|Seiko Epson Corporation]]. *1990 &mdash; Hattori Seiko Co., Ltd. is renamed Seiko Corporation. *1996 &mdash; Seikosha Co., Ltd. is divided into Seiko Precision Inc. and Seiko Clock Inc. *1997 &mdash; Seiko Instruments & Electronics is renamed [[Seiko Instruments|Seiko Instruments Inc.]] *2007 &mdash; Seiko Corporation is renamed Seiko Holdings Corporation.<ref name="seiko history">{{cite web | title = Seiko Holdings history | publisher = Seiko Holdings | url = http://www.seiko.co.jp/en/corporate/history/index.php | accessdate = 2009-10-02 }}{{en icon}}</ref> *1 October 2009 &mdash; Seiko Instruments becomes a wholly owned subsidiary of Seiko Holdings. [[File:081MC.JPG|thumb|Seikosha wall clock]]
